WEBVTT

00:21.154 --> 00:23.489
(tires screeching)

00:23.491 --> 00:25.157
D'oh!

00:25.159 --> 00:26.558
(tires screeching)

00:26.560 --> 00:28.360
(grunts)

00:29.295 --> 00:31.463
(grunting)

00:41.674 --> 00:43.242
(snoring)

00:43.244 --> 00:45.377
(groans)

00:45.379 --> 00:47.579
(humming)

00:47.581 --> 00:49.648
(humming)

00:51.885 --> 00:53.552
Well, if ain't
my next-door neighbor,

00:53.554 --> 00:54.753
King Toot.

00:54.755 --> 00:55.988
Moe.

00:55.990 --> 00:57.389
How many times I
got to tell you

00:57.391 --> 00:59.391
not to throw your trash
in my Dumpster?

00:59.393 --> 01:01.193
Oh, come on, Szyslak.

01:01.195 --> 01:04.029
I got to make space in the store
for my new side business--

01:04.031 --> 01:07.533
a tanning salon that secretly
has cameras in the beds,

01:07.535 --> 01:12.037
which feeds into my Web site,
www.tancams.com.

01:12.039 --> 01:13.672
That is registered.

01:13.674 --> 01:15.040
Yeah, sounds great.

01:15.042 --> 01:17.242
Maybe then you could afford
to rent your own Dumpster.

01:17.244 --> 01:18.844
I like my current deal.

01:18.846 --> 01:20.913
Free. Of. Charge.

01:22.882 --> 01:24.383
(grunting)

01:24.385 --> 01:25.751
I'll eat your hair!

01:25.753 --> 01:28.387
You call that a testicle kick?

01:28.389 --> 01:29.588
(tires screech)

01:29.590 --> 01:31.590
All right, you two, break it up.

01:31.592 --> 01:33.258
Drive on, asphalt cowboy,

01:33.260 --> 01:35.928
or I'll squeeze his brain out
like an edamame.

01:35.930 --> 01:37.362
Eh, uh, a what?

01:37.364 --> 01:39.898
Those beans you eat
before your sushi comes.

01:39.900 --> 01:41.433
Oh, salt peas.

01:41.435 --> 01:44.069
I call them salt peas.

01:44.071 --> 01:46.905
Look, Officer, after 20 years
of being neighbors,

01:46.907 --> 01:48.640
tempers sometimes flare up.

01:48.642 --> 01:50.275
Moe's a good guy.

01:50.277 --> 01:51.910
No, no, no, it's my fault.

01:51.912 --> 01:53.579
I'm a hothead.

01:53.581 --> 01:56.081
I ain't got no beef
with you, Toot.

01:56.083 --> 01:57.749
(whispering): You better stay
out of my Dumpster.

01:57.751 --> 01:59.718
I've also been
stealing the catalogs

01:59.720 --> 02:02.087
out of your mailbox.

02:02.089 --> 02:04.089
(punching,
instruments clattering)

02:04.091 --> 02:06.158
(grunting)

02:08.261 --> 02:10.262
(screaming)

02:10.264 --> 02:12.264
It's my Dumpster!

02:12.266 --> 02:14.333
(screaming continues)

02:20.940 --> 02:22.608
(both growling)

02:22.610 --> 02:24.109
And that's the
terrifying tale

02:24.111 --> 02:27.279
of how the Quebec Nordiques
became...

02:27.281 --> 02:30.115
the Colorado Avalanche.

02:30.117 --> 02:31.316
Oh, no!

02:31.318 --> 02:33.585
King Toot's is closed!

02:33.587 --> 02:36.321
Dad, you're going to have
to take me to...

02:36.323 --> 02:38.490
the big box music store.

02:38.492 --> 02:40.859
Look at all
these monstrosities.

02:40.861 --> 02:43.295
HOMER: Lisa, how many times
have I told you

02:43.297 --> 02:45.631
to bow down
to our corporate overlords?

02:45.633 --> 02:47.699
(Lisa groans)

02:47.701 --> 02:49.701
(doorbell dings)

02:49.703 --> 02:51.136
Hmm.
Hmm.

02:51.138 --> 02:53.205
It's like some kind
of guitar central.

02:54.807 --> 02:56.041
Hmm.

02:56.043 --> 02:57.142
(groans)

02:57.144 --> 02:59.611
Hmm. Hmm.

02:59.613 --> 03:01.980
Midlife crisis
at 12 o'clock.

03:01.982 --> 03:03.682
Mm-hmm.

03:03.684 --> 03:05.317
Okay, let me guess, dude.

03:05.319 --> 03:07.886
You're an axman; you're
looking to score a new blade.

03:07.888 --> 03:09.354
Stig.

03:09.356 --> 03:11.957
(chuckles) You've got a name
that's not a name.

03:11.959 --> 03:13.325
So what's your poison, bro?

03:13.327 --> 03:15.060
Les Paul?
Straight up Gibson?

03:15.062 --> 03:17.029
No, no, no, classic Strat,
am I right?

03:17.031 --> 03:19.331
Oh, I don't have what it takes
to play guitar.

03:19.333 --> 03:22.534
I mean, I'm no Joe Walsh
in the brains department.

03:22.536 --> 03:24.503
(chuckles) Who is?

03:24.505 --> 03:26.138
Look, you don't have the weak,

03:26.140 --> 03:28.707
womanly fingers
of a guitar princess.

03:28.709 --> 03:30.042
You, my friend,

03:30.044 --> 03:32.711
have the muscular stumps
of a bass man.

03:32.713 --> 03:34.680
Try this on.

03:34.682 --> 03:36.748
(note plays loudly)

03:38.218 --> 03:40.352
What the rock?

03:40.354 --> 03:42.387
(chuckles)
Now that was a lick.

03:42.389 --> 03:43.689
I did a lick?

03:43.691 --> 03:44.890
Keep them coming.

03:44.892 --> 03:46.825
(notes repeating)

03:46.827 --> 03:48.360
Yes, now bob your head.

03:48.362 --> 03:51.096
Bob it, bob it, bob it.

03:51.098 --> 03:55.033
Dude, usually it takes years
to learn such neck confidence.

03:55.035 --> 03:56.735
Now check this out.

03:56.737 --> 03:58.804
♪

04:01.107 --> 04:02.608
Oh, my God.

04:02.610 --> 04:04.576
I'm amazing.

04:04.578 --> 04:05.844
Dude, you're already

04:05.846 --> 04:07.980
one of the greatest bass
players of all time.

04:09.215 --> 04:10.415
Okay.

04:10.417 --> 04:12.584
Now... Oh, how are you set
for stage lights?

04:12.586 --> 04:14.052
I'm not set at all.

04:14.054 --> 04:16.922
Ooh, what about gels?

04:16.924 --> 04:19.024
This is embarrassing
to admit, Stig,

04:19.026 --> 04:21.793
but I haven't even thought
about gels.

04:21.795 --> 04:23.161
(Marge humming)

04:24.264 --> 04:25.697
(bass playing loudly)

04:25.699 --> 04:27.299
(gasps)

04:31.070 --> 04:32.304
(screams)

04:33.573 --> 04:35.607
What is that racket?!

04:35.609 --> 04:36.975
Music!

04:36.977 --> 04:39.278
Beautiful music!

04:39.280 --> 04:40.912
What?!

04:40.914 --> 04:42.614
Beautiful music, baby.

04:42.616 --> 04:44.316
The bass guitar?

04:44.318 --> 04:46.785
This doesn't really
seem like you.

04:46.787 --> 04:48.120
Sure it is.

04:48.122 --> 04:50.389
You know I've always loved
laying things down.

04:50.391 --> 04:52.090
Grooves are just the latest.

04:52.092 --> 04:53.425
(groans)

04:53.427 --> 04:55.093
I feel a powerful connection

04:55.095 --> 04:57.262
to the history
of famous bass players.

04:57.264 --> 04:59.264
Like what's-his-name
from The Who.

04:59.266 --> 05:01.266
Or that guy from Led Zeppelin

05:01.268 --> 05:03.268
who wasn't Page,
Plant or Bonham.

05:03.270 --> 05:05.971
Those are the only two
I know for sure.

05:05.973 --> 05:08.840
It's so cool to have
another musician in the family!

05:08.842 --> 05:11.777
Oh, yeah, and you know what
the great thing is about music?

05:11.779 --> 05:14.112
It's so easy.

05:14.114 --> 05:16.281
Uh, well, to truly master
an instrument

05:16.283 --> 05:17.349
you'll need years of...

05:17.351 --> 05:19.384
So easy.

05:20.353 --> 05:21.620
(bass playing)

05:21.622 --> 05:23.555
(gasping)

05:26.859 --> 05:28.927
(siren wailing)
(gasps)

05:31.164 --> 05:32.864
(groans)

05:35.468 --> 05:36.868
(gasps)

05:36.870 --> 05:38.236
Oh!

05:43.276 --> 05:45.711
Ooh!

05:45.713 --> 05:47.012
(groans)

05:49.982 --> 05:51.983
MARGE:
<i>I can't take it.</i>

05:51.985 --> 05:54.986
All Homer does
is play that stupid bass.

05:54.988 --> 05:58.490
Doink, doink, doink, doink,
doink, doink, doink.

05:58.492 --> 06:00.225
You're not alone, Marge.

06:00.227 --> 06:03.028
A man gets older,
has a career, a few kids,

06:03.030 --> 06:05.564
and suddenly there's a hole
in his life

06:05.566 --> 06:09.234
that can only be filled
by jamming.

06:09.236 --> 06:11.570
For my Julius,
it was the drums.

06:11.572 --> 06:13.672
Timothy has
that awful guitar.

06:13.674 --> 06:15.907
Kirk just loves his keyboards.

06:15.909 --> 06:17.676
I never knew
so many women suffered

06:17.678 --> 06:20.145
from extramarital jamming.

06:20.147 --> 06:22.748
Oh, my God, oh, my God,
oh, my God.

06:22.750 --> 06:26.418
What if all the dads
jammed together

06:26.420 --> 06:28.186
in a dad band?!

06:28.188 --> 06:30.355
That way they would play
their horrible music

06:30.357 --> 06:32.657
in one garage at a time.

06:32.659 --> 06:34.693
Marge, you're a genius!

06:34.695 --> 06:36.595
This menu was right--

06:36.597 --> 06:39.998
good things do happen
at 'Zerz.

06:40.000 --> 06:42.067
♪ <i>'Zerz!</i> ♪

06:43.236 --> 06:45.237
(cymbals clattering)

06:45.239 --> 06:46.938
I don't know, guys.

06:46.940 --> 06:48.707
I'm not sure
I'm feeling this.

06:48.709 --> 06:52.377
The bass is kind of known
for being a solo instrument.

06:52.379 --> 06:54.546
What were
our wives thinking?

06:54.548 --> 06:57.015
We probably don't even like
the same tunes.

06:57.017 --> 06:59.117
On the count of three,
everyone say

06:59.119 --> 07:00.552
their favorite kind of music.

07:00.554 --> 07:02.220
One, two, three...

07:02.222 --> 07:03.922
ALL:
Hard-driving rock!

07:03.924 --> 07:05.023
(gasping)

07:05.025 --> 07:06.691
Dads, let's jam!

07:08.528 --> 07:11.396
(rock song playing)

07:11.398 --> 07:13.465
Garage bands rule!

07:16.769 --> 07:17.936
(gasps)

07:17.938 --> 07:20.705
I almost forgot
the most important thing.

07:35.755 --> 07:37.756
(rock song playing)

07:37.758 --> 07:40.091
(song ends)

07:40.093 --> 07:41.927
Great practice, guys.

07:41.929 --> 07:44.095
What do you say we give
it another six hours,

07:44.097 --> 07:45.831
then call it a day?

07:45.833 --> 07:47.499
APU:
Excuse me,

07:47.501 --> 07:50.435
but my wife told me about
your get-out-of-the-house band.

07:50.437 --> 07:52.737
And, uh,
perhaps you need a singer?

07:52.739 --> 07:55.307
Oh, yeah, Apu,

07:55.309 --> 07:57.175
I'm sure you're
a great singer.

07:57.177 --> 08:00.579
But the balance of the band
is really delicate right now,

08:00.581 --> 08:04.449
and we're not really looking
for a world music vibe.

08:04.451 --> 08:06.251
No disrespect to world music.

08:06.253 --> 08:08.286
I love world music.

08:08.288 --> 08:10.522
No, no, I will sing
the classic power ballad

08:10.524 --> 08:13.191
"Hopin' for a Dream"
by my favorite band

08:13.193 --> 08:15.861
from the 1980s, Sungazer.

08:16.796 --> 08:18.296
(clears throat)

08:18.298 --> 08:19.431
Okay, here we go.

08:19.433 --> 08:22.334
♪ When I close my eyes

08:22.336 --> 08:26.338
♪ I wish that
I could fantasize ♪

08:26.340 --> 08:30.609
♪ Pull a dream right
out of the air ♪

08:30.611 --> 08:34.513
♪ Take a chance,
turn it into a prayer. ♪

08:35.548 --> 08:37.382
That sounds nothing
like terrible,

08:37.384 --> 08:38.850
terrible world music.

08:38.852 --> 08:41.720
Why is your voice different
when you sing?

08:41.722 --> 08:44.890
It is because of all the years
I spent at the Kwik-E-Mart...

08:44.892 --> 08:46.324
(rock song playing)

08:46.326 --> 08:48.326
<i>...where classic rock anthems</i>
<i>were piped in</i>

08:48.328 --> 08:49.861
<i>on a never-ending loop.</i>

08:49.863 --> 08:54.332
<i>The endless repetition</i>
<i>drove many clerks to madness.</i>

08:54.334 --> 08:56.334
<i>The only way to maintain</i>
<i>my sanity</i>

08:56.336 --> 08:59.004
<i>was to sing along</i>
<i>until it seemed like</i>

08:59.006 --> 09:00.639
<i>our voices were one.</i>

09:00.641 --> 09:04.009
♪ Hopin' for a dream

09:04.011 --> 09:05.577
♪ <i>Hopin' ♪</i>

09:05.579 --> 09:07.579
♪ Focus like a laser beam

09:07.581 --> 09:11.750
♪ I'll keep fighting
till I want something great ♪

09:11.752 --> 09:14.686
♪ Hopin' for a dream.

09:14.688 --> 09:16.154
(song ends)

09:16.156 --> 09:17.489
Guys, are you feeling this?

09:17.491 --> 09:19.057
Are you feeling this?

09:19.059 --> 09:20.358
I'm feeling it.

09:20.360 --> 09:21.693
I'm definitely
feeling it.

09:21.695 --> 09:24.529
I felt something earlier,
but I was afraid to bring it up.

09:24.531 --> 09:26.598
I think we all
felt something.

09:26.600 --> 09:28.533
We are more than just
a garage band

09:28.535 --> 09:31.036
desperate to do anything other
than hang out with our families.

09:31.038 --> 09:33.672
We are now a cover band.

09:33.674 --> 09:35.240
And we shall be called...

09:35.242 --> 09:36.541
Covercraft.

09:36.543 --> 09:40.111
Because we play covers
and this is our craft.

09:40.113 --> 09:41.880
And it sounds
like Hovercraft.

09:41.882 --> 09:43.381
That was not my intent.

09:43.383 --> 09:45.617
Okay, Covercraft, hands in.

09:45.619 --> 09:46.885
Cover...

09:46.887 --> 09:48.119
ALL:
Craft!

09:53.726 --> 09:57.329
R-O-K-C.

09:58.264 --> 09:59.965
(carnival music playing)

10:06.572 --> 10:08.440
(instruments tuning)

10:10.543 --> 10:13.078
Okay, this crowd is
about to experience

10:13.080 --> 10:15.280
the special magic
of the cover band,

10:15.282 --> 10:17.215
the thrill of live music

10:17.217 --> 10:19.451
without the fear
of hearing anything new.

10:19.453 --> 10:20.585
Hmm?

10:20.587 --> 10:21.820
(sighs)

10:21.822 --> 10:23.722
Apu, what's wrong?

10:23.724 --> 10:25.590
What if, what if
I am no good?

10:25.592 --> 10:27.759
This is the
Cabbage Festival, man.

10:27.761 --> 10:30.095
I-I don't know if
I can face that crowd!

10:30.097 --> 10:31.429
(groans)

10:31.431 --> 10:33.264
Buddy, buddy.
Think of it this way:

10:33.266 --> 10:35.934
you're not singing
in front of all those people,

10:35.936 --> 10:37.769
you're alone
at the Kwik-E-Mart

10:37.771 --> 10:39.270
in the middle of the night.

10:39.272 --> 10:41.139
You just wear this onstage,

10:41.141 --> 10:43.241
and everything will be fine.

10:43.243 --> 10:45.010
(gasps)
My uniform!

10:48.648 --> 10:52.651
All alone at the Kwik-E-Mart.

10:55.454 --> 10:57.088
♪

10:57.090 --> 11:00.125
♪ When I close my eyes

11:00.127 --> 11:04.162
♪ I wish that
I could fantasize ♪

11:04.164 --> 11:07.799
♪ Pull a dream
right out of the air ♪

11:07.801 --> 11:09.167
♪ Take a chance

11:09.169 --> 11:11.169
♪ Turn it into a prayer

11:11.171 --> 11:15.306
♪ Girl, you know
I want to be the guy ♪

11:15.308 --> 11:19.878
♪ With a hunger
burning deep inside ♪

11:19.880 --> 11:23.882
♪ Tonight I wish
upon a falling star ♪

11:23.884 --> 11:28.086
♪ To discover what
my yearnings are... ♪

11:31.323 --> 11:32.691
Everyone loves you, Dad.

11:32.693 --> 11:34.859
You could become
a famous rock star!

11:34.861 --> 11:36.061
Well, son,

11:36.063 --> 11:37.328
I do have the talent.

11:37.330 --> 11:39.297
My mind is full of ideas

11:39.299 --> 11:41.399
for great songs I could write...

11:41.401 --> 11:43.702
down the names of
and then cover.

11:43.704 --> 11:45.236
But then I remember:

11:45.238 --> 11:48.339
I'm just a regular guy,
jamming with my buds.

11:48.341 --> 11:49.708
Oh, sweetie.

11:49.710 --> 11:52.310
This band has brought out
the best in you.

11:52.312 --> 11:55.180
Yeah, you really get that
it's all about the music.

11:55.182 --> 11:56.314
Yep.

11:56.316 --> 11:57.849
It's all about the music.

11:57.851 --> 12:00.752
And it would take a pretty
unforeseen development

12:00.754 --> 12:02.253
to change that.

12:02.255 --> 12:05.423
Pretty unforeseen...

12:08.160 --> 12:11.963
Gentlemen, I think we've found
what we're looking for.

12:15.367 --> 12:17.602
HOMER:
<i>Guys, I really need</i>
<i>your honesty here.</i>

12:17.604 --> 12:19.738
At the Squidport
Senior Jamboree...

12:19.740 --> 12:22.207
was I too in
the pocket?

12:22.209 --> 12:23.875
(Covercraft members gasp)

12:23.877 --> 12:26.177
KIRK:
Freddy Freeman,
Shredder Stevens,

12:26.179 --> 12:28.880
Nick Delacourt and
Peter D'Abbruzio--

12:28.882 --> 12:32.250
you're four of the five guys
from Sungazer!

12:32.252 --> 12:35.420
But where's your lead
singer, Grant LeDavid?

12:35.422 --> 12:37.055
Uh, he passed away.

12:37.057 --> 12:38.056
How?

12:38.058 --> 12:39.591
(whispering)

12:39.593 --> 12:41.960
What kind of erotic
asphyxiation?

12:41.962 --> 12:42.961
(whispering)

12:42.963 --> 12:44.062
Oh...

12:44.064 --> 12:46.064
Apu, you're
the only man

12:46.066 --> 12:47.432
on the entire
Internet

12:47.434 --> 12:50.101
who's got the pure
Sungazer sound.

12:50.103 --> 12:51.736
Will you be our
new lead singer

12:51.738 --> 12:53.738
and join us on
our stadium tour?

12:53.740 --> 12:54.606
Uh...
Oh!
Ooh.

12:54.608 --> 12:57.275
I think I can
answer for Apu.

12:57.277 --> 12:58.476
He's flattered,

12:58.478 --> 13:00.545
but the small-time
success of Covercraft

13:00.547 --> 13:02.614
is all that any of us
have ever wanted.

13:02.616 --> 13:04.082
Uh, actually, I...

13:04.084 --> 13:07.051
Apu has a rich life
here in Springfield:

13:07.053 --> 13:08.953
a store full of
great products,

13:08.955 --> 13:10.822
a lovely
him-type wife,

13:10.824 --> 13:12.590
and eight super kids:

13:12.592 --> 13:15.660
Anoop, Sandeep,
Nabendu, Gheet,

13:15.662 --> 13:18.329
Pria, Uma,
Poonam, Sashi...

13:18.331 --> 13:19.597
Shut your mouth,
I want to do it!

13:19.599 --> 13:20.765
I want to do it!

13:20.767 --> 13:23.768
I want to be a singer
for a real rock band!

13:23.770 --> 13:24.769
SHREDDER STEVENS:
Sun...

13:24.771 --> 13:26.004
ALL:
...gazer!

13:28.974 --> 13:31.075
Gotta say, I'm
kind of jealous

13:31.077 --> 13:33.077
of Apu getting
a break like that.

13:33.079 --> 13:34.279
Not me.

13:34.281 --> 13:35.814
I'm nothing but happy

13:35.816 --> 13:38.483
that our friend is headed
for fame and fortune.

13:38.485 --> 13:40.985
APU:
Tonight we play Las Vegas--

13:40.987 --> 13:44.155
and the theme of
the casino is circus!

13:44.157 --> 13:45.623
Circus!

13:45.625 --> 13:47.292
Ha!

13:47.294 --> 13:48.660
(whimpers)

13:48.662 --> 13:50.795
I want his fame
and fortune so much!

13:50.797 --> 13:54.299
Why must the Lords
of Rock be so cruel?!

13:54.301 --> 13:56.968
(laughing)

13:56.970 --> 13:58.369
Sammy Hagar?

13:58.371 --> 14:00.038
You're not dead.

14:01.340 --> 14:02.774
Damn it!

14:02.776 --> 14:04.809
I told you those jalapeño
poppers had too much breading!

14:04.811 --> 14:06.344
Sorry,
Señor Hagar.

14:06.346 --> 14:08.012
Nah, nah, nah,
it's cool, man.

14:08.014 --> 14:09.814
I went to rock star heaven.

14:09.816 --> 14:13.685
And there was this great back
patio with this sweet fire pit.

14:13.687 --> 14:16.487
If you had the right
wristband-- which I did.

14:16.489 --> 14:17.755
(laughs)

14:22.027 --> 14:24.162
News story in aisle three?
Local clerk,

14:24.164 --> 14:26.364
<i>Apu Nahasapeemapetilon,</i>

14:26.366 --> 14:29.000
<i>is a dead ringer</i>
<i>for a dead singer.</i>

14:29.002 --> 14:31.302
He's living the rock star dream

14:31.304 --> 14:33.171
<i>as front man for</i>
<i>'80s chart-toppers</i>

14:33.173 --> 14:37.208
<i>Sungazer on their Last Final</i>
<i>Hell Re-Freezes Over</i>

14:37.210 --> 14:39.377
<i>Ultimate Good-bye</i>
<i>For Serious This Time</i>

14:39.379 --> 14:41.846
Never Again Part Two
of Question Mark Tour.

14:41.848 --> 14:43.381
Apu and the band appeared

14:43.383 --> 14:44.716
on <i>Saturday Night Live</i>

14:44.718 --> 14:46.317
as the punch line
in a game show sketch.

14:46.319 --> 14:47.685
What's a game show?

14:47.687 --> 14:49.554
Something you make
sketches about.

14:49.556 --> 14:51.222
KENT BROCKMAN:
<i>It looks like Apu</i>
<i>won't be playing</i>

14:51.224 --> 14:54.259
the Cabbage Festival ever again.

14:57.529 --> 14:59.264
Dad, you shouldn't
be jealous of Apu.

14:59.266 --> 15:01.532
Remember, it's all
about the music.

15:01.534 --> 15:02.600
I'm not jealous.

15:02.602 --> 15:03.902
I'm envious.

15:03.904 --> 15:05.169
Jealousy is
when you worry

15:05.171 --> 15:06.604
someone will take
what you have.

15:06.606 --> 15:08.573
Envy is wanting
what someone else has.

15:08.575 --> 15:11.042
What I feel is envy.

15:11.044 --> 15:12.410
Hmm.

15:12.412 --> 15:13.878
Wow, he's
right.

15:13.880 --> 15:14.879
You know what?

15:14.881 --> 15:16.547
Apu leaving is
the best thing

15:16.549 --> 15:17.782
that ever happened
to this band.

15:17.784 --> 15:19.684
We're gonna be
like Genesis

15:19.686 --> 15:21.719
after Peter Gabriel left.

15:21.721 --> 15:23.922
You mean more popular
but not as good?

15:23.924 --> 15:26.624
Phil Collins-era Genesis
is not as good, huh?

15:26.626 --> 15:28.960
"No Reply at All,"
"Land of Confusion,"

15:28.962 --> 15:31.129
"Throwing it All Away,"
"Illegal Alien,"

15:31.131 --> 15:34.732
"I Can't Dance," and I'm sure
I don't need to mention...

15:34.734 --> 15:37.235
"Invisible Touch"!

15:37.237 --> 15:38.303
Hmph!

15:40.873 --> 15:42.373
(Covercraft plays)

15:46.378 --> 15:48.379
(grunts)

15:48.381 --> 15:52.050
You know, we really could
use a new lead singer.

15:52.052 --> 15:54.385
You know, I've been
known to sing a little.

15:54.387 --> 15:57.121
What? So you can also get
famous and bail on us?

15:57.123 --> 15:58.256
You're out of the band!

15:58.258 --> 16:00.658
Well, you can't
just kick him out.

16:00.660 --> 16:03.494
Oh, so you're sticking
up for Yoko here?

16:03.496 --> 16:06.431
Looks like I've got
another Yoko on my hands.

16:06.433 --> 16:08.333
How can there be two Yokos?

16:08.335 --> 16:09.934
Yoko! Yoko!

16:09.936 --> 16:11.269
Yoko! Yoko! Yoko!

16:11.271 --> 16:13.771
All you Yokos
are out of the band!

16:13.773 --> 16:15.840
(grumbling)

16:21.914 --> 16:23.181
Are you okay?

16:23.183 --> 16:24.615
Do I sound okay?

16:24.617 --> 16:26.184
You sound great!

16:26.186 --> 16:29.287
Your licks are really... juicy.

16:29.289 --> 16:31.422
They're not juicy.
My licks are dry.

16:31.424 --> 16:33.291
Dry and scratchy
like a cat's tongue.

16:33.293 --> 16:34.792
You didn't join a band

16:34.794 --> 16:37.261
to become famous like
in   <i>Almost Famous.</i>

16:37.263 --> 16:39.297
You loved playing music
with your friends.

16:39.299 --> 16:41.032
That was enough
to make you happy.

16:41.034 --> 16:42.934
Well, it's not enough anymore.

16:42.936 --> 16:45.136
When something great
happens to one person,

16:45.138 --> 16:47.271
everyone else's life
gets a little worse.

16:47.273 --> 16:49.140
Look it up, it's called physics.

16:49.142 --> 16:50.875
Apu is a good man.

16:50.877 --> 16:54.145
He sent over front row tickets
and backstage passes

16:54.147 --> 16:56.481
to his show at
the Costington Center.

16:56.483 --> 16:58.883
Oh, you mean he
generously invited us

16:58.885 --> 17:00.818
to come watch him
be a rock star?

17:00.820 --> 17:03.021
Stop feeling
sorry for yourself.

17:03.023 --> 17:05.323
Your friend had a wonderful
thing happen to him,

17:05.325 --> 17:08.559
and you are coming with us
to share in his talent.

17:08.561 --> 17:10.528
I'll never have
a per diem.

17:10.530 --> 17:12.630
You don't know
what a per diem is.

17:12.632 --> 17:13.731
Still want one.

17:15.968 --> 17:17.035
Hmph.

17:27.312 --> 17:28.379
Hmph.

17:30.482 --> 17:31.549
Hmph.

17:33.385 --> 17:35.553
Apu wouldn't be able
to sing a note

17:35.555 --> 17:37.688
if I didn't help him get
over his stage fright

17:37.690 --> 17:39.557
with his Kwik-E-Mart shirt.

17:39.559 --> 17:40.691
(gasps)

17:40.693 --> 17:42.260
Backstage pass,

17:42.262 --> 17:45.730
you just became
a payback rage pass.

17:56.075 --> 17:58.376
Look at all this rock star
dressing room stuff.

17:58.378 --> 17:59.710
What a sellout.

17:59.712 --> 18:01.112
Cheese plate...

18:01.114 --> 18:03.381
oh, sorry, <i>cubed</i> cheese plate.

18:03.383 --> 18:07.218
Lemon tea, probably
for his throat.

18:07.220 --> 18:08.753
Mm-hmm!

18:09.721 --> 18:11.055
Let's see how he performs

18:11.057 --> 18:12.590
in front of all those people

18:12.592 --> 18:15.626
without his magic-people-
performing-in-front-of shirt.

18:16.628 --> 18:18.196
(door opens, Homer gasps)

18:18.198 --> 18:20.531
But, Mr. Shredder,
you promised me

18:20.533 --> 18:23.101
after we played my hometown
I could have a day off.

18:23.103 --> 18:25.103
I also promised
I'd kick heroin.

18:25.105 --> 18:26.270
Hmm?

18:26.272 --> 18:28.639
But the tour is
so hard on my family.

18:28.641 --> 18:30.108
My octuplets are being raised

18:30.110 --> 18:31.776
by roadies and bodyguards.

18:31.778 --> 18:33.945
This is
not proper.

18:33.947 --> 18:35.113
Look, Apu.

18:35.115 --> 18:37.248
For 25 years
we wasted money

18:37.250 --> 18:38.916
on women, drugs

18:38.918 --> 18:41.252
and guitars with
live fish inside.

18:41.254 --> 18:43.488
And now we want
to keep it going.

18:43.490 --> 18:45.823
You signed a contract
for a three-year,

18:45.825 --> 18:48.559
57-country tour
at union scale--

18:48.561 --> 18:50.128
no per diem.

18:50.130 --> 18:50.928
(gasps softly)

18:50.930 --> 18:52.864
You're in the band.

18:54.766 --> 18:57.468
Oh, well, I guess it's showtime.

18:57.470 --> 18:58.769
(gasps)

18:58.771 --> 18:59.904
Homer?

18:59.906 --> 19:01.139
I'm sorry, Apu.

19:01.141 --> 19:02.573
I thought you were
living your dream life,

19:02.575 --> 19:04.275
so naturally
I wanted to ruin it.

19:04.277 --> 19:06.410
But now I know things stink,

19:06.412 --> 19:08.479
so I'm okay with it.

19:08.481 --> 19:09.914
Oh, what is
the point?

19:09.916 --> 19:12.950
I am trapped like
a Kwik-E-Mart hot
dog on a roller.

19:12.952 --> 19:15.620
Kwik-E-Mart hot dog, eh?

19:15.622 --> 19:17.688
You want every hot dog
in the store?

19:17.690 --> 19:18.923
Every one?

19:18.925 --> 19:20.358
Okay...

19:30.135 --> 19:32.770
Yeah!
Yeah.
Oh!
Yeah!

19:32.772 --> 19:34.972
FORUM ANNOUNCER:
Ladies and gentlemen,

19:34.974 --> 19:37.808
Tucks Medicated Pads presents...

19:37.810 --> 19:39.644
Sungazer!

19:39.646 --> 19:42.346
(cheering)
Yeah!
All right!

19:43.782 --> 19:44.782
Uh, people?

19:44.784 --> 19:46.317
I am sorry to report

19:46.319 --> 19:48.653
that all the original
members of the band

19:48.655 --> 19:50.121
have been struck down

19:50.123 --> 19:52.823
by a mysterious case
of hot dog poisoning.

19:52.825 --> 19:53.958
(groaning)

19:53.960 --> 19:55.693
Rather than refund your money

19:55.695 --> 19:57.328
or reschedule the show,

19:57.330 --> 19:58.996
we have a surprise for you.

19:58.998 --> 20:01.399
Get ready to rock with a group

20:01.401 --> 20:05.236
that is truly all about
the music-- Covercraft!

20:05.238 --> 20:07.305
♪

